Of course, this is a very straightforward application of the definitions of spherical versus rectangular coordinates. Recall that given a point $p$ with spherical coordinates $\langle \rho, \theta, \phi \rangle,$ we have:
\begin{align*}
x &= \rho\sin\phi\cos\theta,\\
y &= \rho\sin\phi\sin\theta,\\
z &= \rho\cos\phi.
\end{align*}
If $P$ has rectangular coordinates $(2, -1, -2)$, it follows that
\begin{align*}
\rho &= \sqrt{2^2 + (-1)^2 + (-2)^2} = 3,\\
\theta &= \pm\arctan\left(\dfrac{-1}{2}\right),\\
\phi &= \arccos\left(-\dfrac{2}{3}\right).
\end{align*}
Therefore, the rectangular coordinates of the point with spherical coordinates $\langle \rho, \theta, 2\phi \rangle$ are
\begin{align*}
x &= 3\sin\left(2\arccos\left(-\dfrac{2}{3}\right)\right)\cos\left(\pm\arctan\left(\dfrac{-1}{2}\right)\right),\\
y &= 3\sin\left(2\arccos\left(-\dfrac{2}{3}\right)\right)\sin\left(\pm\arctan\left(\dfrac{-1}{2}\right)\right),\\
z &= 3\cos\left(2\arccos\left(-\dfrac{2}{3}\right)\right).
\end{align*}
</think>
